00:50:08.560 --> 00:50:13.380
Because one of the
difficulties that we have trying

00:50:13.380 --> 00:50:18.750
to get collections back from
international institutions is

00:50:18.750 --> 00:50:25.020
that those countries have their
own laws that often declares

00:50:25.020 --> 00:50:30.600
that those things that they hold
are their national patrimony.

00:50:30.600 --> 00:50:35.060
So, for example, Spain
was a conquering country

00:50:35.060 --> 00:50:41.500
of indigenous people and peoples
and took a lot of items back

00:50:41.500 --> 00:50:47.470
to Spain, and there are items
in Spain that are now part

00:50:47.470 --> 00:50:51.840
of their cultural patrimony,
even though they were looted

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:56.280
and stolen and taken from
the indigenous peoples here.

00:50:56.280 --> 00:51:01.680
So it becomes a different kind
of discussion that you have

00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:07.020
with an international
government and you have to go

00:51:07.020 --> 00:51:10.300
through their laws as well.

00:51:10.300 --> 00:51:14.040
And one thing that is
often not addressed,

00:51:14.040 --> 00:51:17.780
even though these items
have a Federal tie,

00:51:17.780 --> 00:51:22.480
they came from Federal lands,
they are part of what's kind

00:51:22.480 --> 00:51:24.880
of considered Federal
property even though I don't

00:51:24.880 --> 00:51:28.610
like to consider our
ancestral remains

00:51:28.610 --> 00:51:32.370
and cultural items in that way.

00:51:33.690 --> 00:51:39.900
And so they're inalienable
from the Federal Government,

00:51:39.900 --> 00:51:45.820
but Native-Americans'
items which are inalienable

00:51:45.820 --> 00:51:53.230
to us it is very difficult
for us to argue to collectors

00:51:53.230 --> 00:51:57.080
and others that there are items
that are inalienable to us

00:51:57.080 --> 00:52:03.500
and to our nations, that no one
has the authority to give away,

00:52:03.500 --> 00:52:06.850
and the only reason why they're
in other people's hands is

00:52:06.850 --> 00:52:09.900
through theft and
looting or some kind

00:52:09.900 --> 00:52:12.070
of illegitimate taking.

00:52:12.070 --> 00:52:20.480
So it's great that we have that
Federal tie-in with many items,

00:52:20.480 --> 00:52:23.650
but there are still many
more where we don't have

00:52:23.650 --> 00:52:28.780
that Federal tie-in and we don't
have any strong Federal law

00:52:28.780 --> 00:52:30.850
that will support the argument

00:52:30.850 --> 00:52:34.660
that these are our
unalienable items

00:52:34.660 --> 00:52:38.770
that could not have been
taken except through theft.

00:52:38.770 --> 00:52:43.820
But I totally missed
your second question.

00:52:43.820 --> 00:52:49.840
&gt;&gt; I was just asking like
if you guys do education

00:52:49.840 --> 00:52:52.850
or outreach programs to
sort of shift or create

00:52:52.850 --> 00:52:55.600
that culture shift to where
people see these items

00:52:55.600 --> 00:52:58.740
for what they are, like
funerary items or human remains,

00:52:58.740 --> 00:53:00.100
and humanize them as opposed

00:53:00.100 --> 00:53:02.860
to just looking at
them behind glass?

00:53:02.860 --> 00:53:06.380
&gt;&gt; Sarah Glass: Yes, I mean we,

00:53:06.380 --> 00:53:10.680
a big part of what the National
NAGPRA Program does is offer

00:53:10.680 --> 00:53:16.300
training, resources, technical
assistance to museums,

00:53:16.300 --> 00:53:19.780
but obviously since we're the
NAGPRA Program we are focused

00:53:19.780 --> 00:53:24.310
on NAGPRA items, domestic
issues, but that doesn't mean

00:53:24.310 --> 00:53:27.010
that we don't still try to
get involved in this kind

00:53:27.010 --> 00:53:29.210
of broader culture shift

00:53:29.210 --> 00:53:32.960
and this broader
application of this work.

00:53:32.960 --> 00:53:35.570
So, for example, my
boss, Melanie O'Brian,

00:53:35.570 --> 00:53:38.040
who is the Manager of the
National NAGPRA Program,

00:53:38.040 --> 00:53:41.160
actually traveled with
an interagency delegation

00:53:41.160 --> 00:53:45.970
to France earlier this year, to
Paris to try to educate and meet

00:53:45.970 --> 00:53:50.810
with government officials
there, our officials to talk

00:53:50.810 --> 00:53:54.280
about why are these
Paris auctions

00:53:54.280 --> 00:54:00.470
of sacred Native-American items
such a big deal, why do we care?

00:54:00.470 --> 00:54:04.280
Because there's just not
that recognition, right,

00:54:04.280 --> 00:54:06.890
or even language,
even the translations.

00:54:06.890 --> 00:54:10.890
When you say a sacred object and
that has a very specific meaning

00:54:10.890 --> 00:54:15.720
under US law and to
different tribes over here,

00:54:15.720 --> 00:54:17.620
when you say sacred in French

00:54:17.620 --> 00:54:20.870
that doesn't necessarily
equate in the same way.

00:54:20.870 --> 00:54:28.320
So, yes, we do try to do our
best to educate to the extent

00:54:28.320 --> 00:54:34.300
under the law, for me at least
being restricted by that.

00:54:34.300 --> 00:54:39.060
When I do get calls about
people asking about mummies

00:54:39.060 --> 00:54:43.280
or other kind of grave goods,
I remember being shocked

00:54:43.280 --> 00:54:47.380
when I went through to Italy
and went through museums

00:54:47.380 --> 00:54:51.330
and just saw body after body
after body from Vesuvius

00:54:51.330 --> 00:54:54.390
and was kind of taken
aback by that,

00:54:54.390 --> 00:54:59.410
but it's just a more normal
practice still I would say

00:54:59.410 --> 00:55:01.750
in some parts of the world.

00:55:01.750 --> 00:55:09.740
But here luckily with that
kind of shift in these fields,

00:55:09.740 --> 00:55:12.350
in archaeology, I was an
archaeologist undergrad

00:55:12.350 --> 00:55:18.870
and anthropologist and
museum studies, you know,

00:55:18.870 --> 00:55:21.770
that's the new guard
I think moving

00:55:21.770 --> 00:55:25.270
in to start shifting our
perceptions of that and not just

00:55:25.270 --> 00:55:27.280
because NAGPRA says you have to,

00:55:27.280 --> 00:55:31.140
but because this is what's
the right thing to do as well.

00:55:31.140 --> 00:55:36.880
So I think that's the direction
that most people, not everyone,

00:55:36.880 --> 00:55:40.870
but most people are
tending towards.

00:55:40.870 --> 00:55:42.590
Maybe I'm optimistic.

00:55:42.590 --> 00:55:45.570
&gt;&gt; Emily Palus: If I could,
I want to touch on this, too,

00:55:45.570 --> 00:55:48.410
because I think a lot of
it comes down to consent,

00:55:48.410 --> 00:55:50.560
consent of the descendent
community

00:55:50.560 --> 00:55:53.010
and what is a cultural norm.

00:55:53.010 --> 00:55:58.400
And so what's so pivotal about
NAGPRA is that it describes

00:55:58.400 --> 00:56:00.950
that while the Federal
Government actually had this

00:56:00.950 --> 00:56:04.640
policy of excavating and
study and display was

00:56:04.640 --> 00:56:06.650
in the public interest
and then reversed

00:56:06.650 --> 00:56:09.830
that because recognizing
that Indian people,

00:56:09.830 --> 00:56:13.020
Native-American people have the
right to control the disposition

00:56:13.020 --> 00:56:19.780
of their ancestors and not
the 500 and plus tribes

00:56:19.780 --> 00:56:21.610
in Native-Alaskan communities,

00:56:21.610 --> 00:56:24.660
not everyone has the
exact same world view.

00:56:24.660 --> 00:56:28.250
And there are some tribes
that will take remains

00:56:28.250 --> 00:56:30.140
and rebury them on their
lands, there are some tribes

00:56:30.140 --> 00:56:32.760
that will take remains
and rebury them as close

00:56:32.760 --> 00:56:35.530
to the original interment as
possible, there are some tribes

00:56:35.530 --> 00:56:37.670
that allow study,
there are some tribes

00:56:37.670 --> 00:56:40.500
that allow intrusive
study, it's their consent

00:56:40.500 --> 00:56:42.600
and I think what it
comes down to is consent.

00:56:42.600 --> 00:56:46.850
But I agree that sometimes it's
sort of shocking when you walk

00:56:46.850 --> 00:56:49.440
into a museum and see
human remains everywhere.

00:56:49.440 --> 00:56:54.220
I was doing a behind-the-scenes
tour, a repository review

00:56:54.220 --> 00:56:57.640
of an institution that
held Federal collections,

00:56:57.640 --> 00:57:00.000
and we walked into the
physical anthropology labs,

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:02.250
physical anthropology
human remains.

00:57:02.250 --> 00:57:08.050
And the curator opened
up these wardrobe doors

00:57:08.050 --> 00:57:13.290
and there was just shelves
of skulls, and I fell back

00:57:13.290 --> 00:57:17.960
because I, well, one, I didn't
know that was coming and even

00:57:17.960 --> 00:57:20.570
if I'm not a Native-American I
think a little heads-up would

00:57:20.570 --> 00:57:25.410
have been, excuse me, a little
warning that that would have,

00:57:25.410 --> 00:57:28.830
yes, that this was happening.

00:57:28.830 --> 00:57:35.500
And then there was a gasp,
one of my colleagues gasped.

00:57:35.500 --> 00:57:40.710
And she said, oh, no, no,
it's okay, they're from Peru,

00:57:40.710 --> 00:57:44.560
they're not subject to
NAGPRA so it's okay.

00:57:44.560 --> 00:57:49.990
And then also actually
the same institution,

00:57:49.990 --> 00:57:52.580
and now the story I'm telling
is about from 15 years ago,

00:57:52.580 --> 00:57:54.510
they've changed course
dramatically,

00:57:54.510 --> 00:57:58.060
but there was a display of --

00:57:58.060 --> 00:58:01.000
you push the button so it's
interactive, you push the button

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:03.460
and this woman on the
phone says, hello, hello,

00:58:03.460 --> 00:58:05.600
I found something in my garage.

00:58:05.600 --> 00:58:08.790
And the story is that this
woman went into her garage

00:58:08.790 --> 00:58:12.080
and there was a box and she
opened up the box and, well,

00:58:12.080 --> 00:58:16.230
there was mummified, naturally
mummified human remains.

00:58:16.230 --> 00:58:19.090
And the story was that her
husband or his friends had gone

00:58:19.090 --> 00:58:21.640
over to Mexico and
brought them back.

00:58:21.640 --> 00:58:26.410
I'm not sure how they ended up
at this museum, but the story

00:58:26.410 --> 00:58:29.650
and how it was presented was
this kind of, oh, my gosh,

00:58:29.650 --> 00:58:31.830
this woman walked into her
garage and found this box

00:58:31.830 --> 00:58:34.300
with mummified remains in it.

00:58:34.300 --> 00:58:38.150
And, no, that kind of display,
that actually was sensational,

00:58:38.150 --> 00:58:40.520
but that's just not appropriate.

00:58:40.520 --> 00:58:43.600
And I think that that
story is changing.

00:58:43.600 --> 00:58:45.230
I guess the last thing I
would say is I'm grateful

00:58:45.230 --> 00:58:47.970
for this opportunity to come
here and talk to this group

00:58:47.970 --> 00:58:52.720
about this statute with
my esteemed colleagues.

