00:59:22.320 --> 00:59:26.310
with tribes implementing
programs on the ground.

00:59:26.310 --> 00:59:32.360
So having membership that's
representative of all of us

00:59:32.360 --> 00:59:36.090
in the United States I think
really tells a strong story

00:59:36.090 --> 00:59:38.900
about some of the
issues and the programs

00:59:38.900 --> 00:59:41.800
and the education we're trying
to do, that we're backed

00:59:41.800 --> 00:59:45.280
by a diverse community
of individuals,

00:59:45.280 --> 00:59:50.430
not just indigenous
Americans but everyone.

00:59:50.430 --> 00:59:53.580
So I encourage you to
participate in some

00:59:53.580 --> 00:59:55.420
of the programs the
Association has.

00:59:55.420 --> 01:00:01.180
We just got done with a
Repatriation Conference

01:00:01.180 --> 01:00:03.530
where there were
tribal practitioners,

01:00:03.530 --> 01:00:09.580
spiritual leaders, museum
curators, foreign institutions,

01:00:09.580 --> 01:00:16.300
lawyers and a variety of
people working together

01:00:16.300 --> 01:00:21.640
to find ways towards more
success in repatriation efforts,

01:00:21.640 --> 01:00:25.800
not just with NAGPRA but also
those things that fall outside

01:00:25.800 --> 01:00:28.800
of NAGPRA or in foreign
institutions.

01:00:28.800 --> 01:00:32.060
So there are opportunities
to be educated

01:00:32.060 --> 01:00:35.390
and I think there's a lot
in the media right now,

01:00:35.390 --> 01:00:41.450
so if you search auctions,
Native-American cultural items,

01:00:41.450 --> 01:00:44.930
if you look on the Association's
website you're going

01:00:44.930 --> 01:00:49.460
to find a lot of
information available for you.

01:00:49.460 --> 01:00:51.580
&gt;&gt; Sarah Glass: Yes, it is
becoming more well known

01:00:51.580 --> 01:00:56.030
for sure, these issues
are getting attention now

01:00:56.030 --> 01:01:00.970
like never before, so
that's a positive thing.

01:01:00.970 --> 01:01:03.450
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: The sad
thing to me is that it wasn't

01:01:03.450 --> 01:01:09.950
until 1990, wow,
yikes, that's terrible.

01:01:09.950 --> 01:01:12.910
Anyone else?

01:01:12.910 --> 01:01:15.690
Oh, come on?

01:01:22.150 --> 01:01:26.270
&gt;&gt; So you said that the NAGPRA
Program is an imperfect law,

01:01:26.270 --> 01:01:30.020
are there other countries
that are doing it right

01:01:30.020 --> 01:01:34.080
or have it a little bit closer,
that you kind of hold as, oh,

01:01:34.080 --> 01:01:36.890
this is how they're doing it,
like maybe we can take things

01:01:36.890 --> 01:01:41.800
from them, or are we like doing
the best we can and we're kind

01:01:41.800 --> 01:01:46.240
of at the end, you
know, beginning of it?

01:01:46.240 --> 01:01:48.280
&gt;&gt; Sarah Glass: That's a good
question, it's a great question.

01:01:48.280 --> 01:01:54.340
Yes, it just, so it's
been almost 30 years

01:01:54.340 --> 01:01:57.300
since NAGPRA was passed and
I think it's safe to say

01:01:57.300 --> 01:02:01.670
that no one that was drafting
NAGPRA 30 years ago really

01:02:01.670 --> 01:02:06.900
thought that this work was
still going to be going on now

01:02:06.900 --> 01:02:08.280
in the way that it has.

01:02:08.280 --> 01:02:12.560
And, as we've mentioned, the
statistics are still kind

01:02:12.560 --> 01:02:16.400
of mindboggling about just
how much is still left to do.

01:02:16.400 --> 01:02:21.920
And there's gaps, as
we've pointed out.

01:02:21.920 --> 01:02:26.500
So there are other countries
that have laws in place

01:02:26.500 --> 01:02:30.120
to address these
similar types of issues.

01:02:30.120 --> 01:02:34.280
Australia being one of
them, New Zealand, Canada.

01:02:34.280 --> 01:02:39.270
So other countries that
have these kind of histories

01:02:39.270 --> 01:02:45.500
of indigenous populations,
imperialistic people moving in,

01:02:45.500 --> 01:02:50.660
power imbalances that are
inherent in then the power,

01:02:50.660 --> 01:02:53.510
the country that takes power.

01:02:53.510 --> 01:02:56.680
I don't -- maybe
someone else can speak

01:02:56.680 --> 01:02:59.940
to if they're doing any better
than what NAGPRA is doing,

01:02:59.940 --> 01:03:07.970
but I know that often
this is used as an example

01:03:07.970 --> 01:03:13.800
of how you can at least try
to shift that power imbalance

01:03:13.800 --> 01:03:22.130
and try to start doing that
work of righting past wrongs.

01:03:22.130 --> 01:03:26.950
I know another international
kind of outreach thing

01:03:26.950 --> 01:03:30.500
that the National NAGPRA Program
did, we actually sent staff

01:03:30.500 --> 01:03:37.550
to Japan because they have a
very strong centralized program

01:03:37.550 --> 01:03:40.870
for acknowledging and
putting out a list

01:03:40.870 --> 01:03:42.750
of their national treasures,

01:03:42.750 --> 01:03:48.750
things that they consider
national cultural treasures

01:03:48.750 --> 01:03:53.850
from dance to art, to
all sorts of things.

01:03:53.850 --> 01:03:56.980
And so that was a kind

01:03:56.980 --> 01:03:59.830
of cross-cultural
learning experience about,

01:03:59.830 --> 01:04:01.130
oh, how do you do it?

01:04:01.130 --> 01:04:04.130
And it really just comes down
to every country is different,

01:04:04.130 --> 01:04:06.920
every situation is different.

01:04:06.920 --> 01:04:10.870
The United States has
such strong protections

01:04:10.870 --> 01:04:16.320
of personal property and that
property law that can get

01:04:16.320 --> 01:04:20.330
so gray sometimes
or so hard to fight

01:04:20.330 --> 01:04:23.470
when it's private property,

01:04:23.470 --> 01:04:26.300
and I don't ever see the
United States saying, yes,

01:04:26.300 --> 01:04:29.480
we're going to take
your private property

01:04:29.480 --> 01:04:31.700
because it's the
right thing to do.

01:04:31.700 --> 01:04:36.410
But, sorry, I rambled there.

01:04:37.610 --> 01:04:40.440
&gt;&gt; Shannon Keller O'Loughlin:
Well, I'm looking for a day

01:04:40.440 --> 01:04:44.730
that we will have
some kind of mechanism

01:04:44.730 --> 01:04:49.000
to allow the taking
of stolen property.

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:54.160
And, as I said earlier, most
of the cultural patrimony

01:04:54.160 --> 01:04:56.550
and sacred patrimony
and funerary items

01:04:56.550 --> 01:05:00.300
and human remains were
taken illegitimately

01:05:00.300 --> 01:05:03.800
because they could be
considered inalienable

01:05:03.800 --> 01:05:07.380
from those nations,
from those tribes.

01:05:07.380 --> 01:05:11.750
NAGPRA really is I hate
to say the gold standard,

01:05:11.750 --> 01:05:18.120
but it is really the best
out there for a process

01:05:18.120 --> 01:05:22.120
by which indigenous peoples can
have the items repatriated back

01:05:22.120 --> 01:05:23.500
to them.

01:05:23.500 --> 01:05:26.560
Other countries are much better

01:05:26.560 --> 01:05:29.810
at protecting their
national heritage than we are

01:05:29.810 --> 01:05:33.210
and don't checkerboard
the protections

01:05:33.210 --> 01:05:35.330
up like the United
States does because of

01:05:35.330 --> 01:05:40.680
that private property
type of mentality

01:05:40.680 --> 01:05:42.680
that we have here in the US.

01:05:42.680 --> 01:05:45.630
So in other countries
you see mechanisms

01:05:45.630 --> 01:05:50.030
by which all land is
protected so no one can go in

01:05:50.030 --> 01:05:54.500
and start digging and all of
a sudden declare ownership

01:05:54.500 --> 01:05:58.160
of that human burial
or of those items

01:05:58.160 --> 01:06:00.270
that they found in the ground.

01:06:00.270 --> 01:06:05.350
And it's not like that here and
what's even more interesting is

01:06:05.350 --> 01:06:06.920
that we do have Federal law

01:06:06.920 --> 01:06:10.540
in the United States
that's highly prohibitive

01:06:10.540 --> 01:06:16.080
of the same type of private
property issue when it comes

01:06:16.080 --> 01:06:20.210
to endangered species
and collecting

01:06:20.210 --> 01:06:25.820
or selling endangered species,
such as the Golden Eagle

01:06:25.820 --> 01:06:29.010
and Bald Eagle Protection Act.

01:06:29.010 --> 01:06:34.950
So if I'm standing at my house
and a Bald Eagle dies and falls

01:06:34.950 --> 01:06:40.330
in front of me I have absolutely
no rights to that animal

01:06:40.330 --> 01:06:46.340
or parts of that animal, I have
to call someone to take it.

01:06:46.340 --> 01:06:54.470
But if I find something in my
land, if I find amazing pottery

01:06:54.470 --> 01:06:59.120
or even human remains
depending on what state I live

01:06:59.120 --> 01:07:01.970
in there may be no other laws

01:07:01.970 --> 01:07:08.170
that protect the affiliated
tribe's rights to those things

01:07:08.170 --> 01:07:14.090
and I can start my own museum
in my garage with what I find

01:07:14.090 --> 01:07:16.630
in my own, on my own
private property.

01:07:16.630 --> 01:07:20.060
So there's a little bit
of disparate thinking,

01:07:20.060 --> 01:07:23.410
unconnected thinking when
we're looking at protection

01:07:23.410 --> 01:07:29.360
of Native-American cultural
heritage and it really goes back

01:07:29.360 --> 01:07:38.170
into how our Federal laws
apply to indigenous peoples,

01:07:38.170 --> 01:07:44.230
which is based on this kind of
schizophrenic notion that tribes

01:07:44.230 --> 01:07:46.360
and Indian peoples are sovereign

01:07:46.360 --> 01:07:48.850
but at the same time
they're inferior.

01:07:48.850 --> 01:07:50.430
And so depending on the whims

01:07:50.430 --> 01:07:55.870
of the current Administration
oftentimes our Federal policies

01:07:55.870 --> 01:07:59.790
protecting Native-Americans and
Native-American heritage kind

01:07:59.790 --> 01:08:04.960
of wings one way or the other
because our Federal laws are

01:08:04.960 --> 01:08:09.900
so schizophrenic when protecting
indigenous peoples here.

