I started under a NAGPRA
grant, not knowing anything

01:08:42.740 --> 01:08:47.430
about NAGPRA, never even knew
that my ancestor remains were

01:08:47.430 --> 01:08:49.210
in museums and other
institutions,

01:08:49.210 --> 01:08:51.880
so it's been an incredible
education

01:08:51.880 --> 01:08:54.100
that I've had since
the year 2000.

01:08:54.100 --> 01:08:59.930
What I have seen in that
time thanks to NAGPRA a lot

01:08:59.930 --> 01:09:01.640
of ancestors are returning home,

01:09:01.640 --> 01:09:05.500
a lot of their belongings
are returning home,

01:09:05.500 --> 01:09:07.530
and that's been phenomenal.

01:09:07.530 --> 01:09:11.660
What I've also seen in my own
community is we are beefing

01:09:11.660 --> 01:09:13.760
up our travel codes
and ordinances

01:09:13.760 --> 01:09:18.010
to protect our ancestral
remains and resting places,

01:09:18.010 --> 01:09:20.400
but also the states,
I'm starting

01:09:20.400 --> 01:09:21.900
to see more states take that on.

01:09:21.900 --> 01:09:26.840
Wisconsin just passed a revised
Burial Sites Preservation Law

01:09:26.840 --> 01:09:31.520
that protects burials,
categorized, or catalogued

01:09:31.520 --> 01:09:36.750
or uncatalogued, and it actually
empowered our inter-tribal

01:09:36.750 --> 01:09:39.210
repatriation community
in Wisconsin

01:09:39.210 --> 01:09:44.860
when ancestral remains are
discovered during certain

01:09:44.860 --> 01:09:47.390
projects, excavations,
whether it's on private land

01:09:47.390 --> 01:09:50.640
or public land it is left

01:09:50.640 --> 01:09:53.710
up to the inter-tribal
repatriation committee

01:09:53.710 --> 01:09:56.680
to determine disposition
of those human remains,

01:09:56.680 --> 01:09:58.580
where they're going to
be repatriated, buried,

01:09:58.580 --> 01:09:59.900
what happens with them.

01:09:59.900 --> 01:10:03.650
So on top of what we have
Federally we're starting

01:10:03.650 --> 01:10:08.510
to see tribes and states take
a more proactive approach

01:10:08.510 --> 01:10:12.100
in beefing up their
laws to prohibit

01:10:12.100 --> 01:10:15.200
and protect ancestral
burial remains.

01:10:18.020 --> 01:10:19.500
&gt;&gt; Jane Sanchez: Okay.

01:10:19.500 --> 01:10:28.490
I think it's time to
begin our closing.

01:10:28.490 --> 01:10:30.970
I'd like to thank
everyone involved

01:10:30.970 --> 01:10:33.090
in making this Panel possible.

01:10:33.090 --> 01:10:36.670
Shannon, Emily and
Sarah, thank you so much

01:10:36.670 --> 01:10:38.280
for joining us this evening.

01:10:38.280 --> 01:10:41.840
Thank you, all, for
spending your evening with us

01:10:41.840 --> 01:10:44.500
and celebrating the
70th Anniversary

01:10:44.500 --> 01:10:47.800
of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights.

01:10:47.800 --> 01:10:52.150
We've come a long way since the
adoption of the Declaration,

01:10:52.150 --> 01:10:55.010
but we must also acknowledge
that we have not lived

01:10:55.010 --> 01:10:57.130
up to its full vision.

01:10:57.130 --> 01:11:00.500
So as we celebrate
tonight we must also commit

01:11:00.500 --> 01:11:05.450
to working harder to make the
Declaration's ideal a reality

01:11:05.450 --> 01:11:07.210
in people's lives.

01:11:07.210 --> 01:11:10.870
We must support the work
of human rights defenders,

01:11:10.870 --> 01:11:15.880
nongovernmental organizations,
experts, policymakers,

01:11:15.880 --> 01:11:22.040
journalists and all peoples of
conscience, and we must continue

01:11:22.040 --> 01:11:25.540
until the timeless and
universal principles

01:11:25.540 --> 01:11:29.650
in the Declaration become
not just an inspiration

01:11:29.650 --> 01:11:33.560
or an aspiration but the
foundation of life for all

01:11:33.560 --> 01:11:35.820
of the world's people.

01:11:35.820 --> 01:11:39.620
Thank you, once again, and
have a great evening, everyone.

01:11:39.620 --> 01:11:40.920
Thank you.

01:11:40.920 --> 01:11:42.000
[applause]

